{{Infobox television episode | title = The American Saddlebred | series = A Celebration of Horses <!-- without italics or formatting. Wikilinking optional. --> | image = File:1994ASHA-Article-Cover (cropped).jpg | image_size = 220 <!-- raw number. "px" not required. --> | alt = 1993 AHSA Award | caption = Cover of ''American Saddlebred'' magazine featuring William Shatner | season = 1993—1994 | series_no = 1 | episode = Pilot | director = | writer = | narrator = David Henry | teleplay = Betty Wills | story = William Shatner, impromptu behind-the-scenes | producer = Axiom Entertainment | music = ASCAP | photographer = Scott Jewett | editor = Joe Dixon | production = G | airdate = 2003 November <!-- {{no way to know the exact day as each station has different scheduling}} --> | length = 28:30 | presenter = WKNO-Memphis | guests = William Shatner | awards = 1993 AHSA Award for Broadcast Media Excellence<ref name="Award">{{cite web | url=http://www.thewillsranch.com/Shatner.html | title=A celebration of horses | accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref> | season_list = | prev = | next = | episode_list = }} '''A Celebration of Horses: The American Saddlebred''' was a half-hour television special about the [[American Saddlebred]] horse breed. As a pilot episode, it was scheduled for four national releases from November 1993 to October 1995 on the [[Public Broadcasting Service (PBS)]] in the [[United States]] on 56 regional affiliates, and was also broadcast into Canada. The program starred actor and horse enthusiast [[William Shatner]]. Most of the segments were taped on location with Shatner at his [[Belle Reve Farm]], and at the [[Lexington Junior League Horse Show]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky]].
==Concept and creation== [[File:The American Saddlebred magazine 1994.jpg|thumb|upright| ''American Saddlebred'' coverage of the episode.]]
The documentary was produced as the pilot episode for a proposed PBS series titled ''A Celebration of Horses''. The series was designed to showcase the history of various horse breeds, the evolution of equestrian sports and the preparation required for horse show competition. The series' origins correlated with the stated vision of former [[United States Equestrian Federation|ASHA]] president Judy Werner, who said in the organization's 1989 Annual Meeting, "Don't we all feel that a television, radio, or magazine advertisement focusing on 'The Sport of Showing Horses,' regardless of the breed, would make us all proud? Convey to the public a positive feeling about the sport? Be effective? I do, and I guarantee you that is going to happen..."<ref name=TASB>{{cite journal | journal = The American Saddlebred | publisher=American Saddlebred Horse Association|title= TV Series Featuring Saddlebreds Honored | page=88 | date=January 1994}}</ref> The series concept originated with executive producer Betty Wills, a competitor in equine sports. Patricia Nichols, former executive secretary of the [[American Saddlebred Horse Association]];<ref name=SHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.saddlehorsereport.com/news.aspx?cid=8088#.VvUoDMccP6Q|title=Patricia Nichols Dies|publisher=The Saddle Horse Report|date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> and Lynn Weatherman, former editor of ''The American Saddlebred'' magazine,<ref name=EQUUS>{{cite magazine|url=http://equusmagazine.com/article/weatherman_041506|title=Saddlebred Legend Lynn Weatherman Dies|publisher=EQUUS Magazine|date=April 15, 2006}}</ref> participated as technical advisors in the production and also provided some of the [[stock footage]].
==Cast== *William Shatner, celebrity guest host *[[Marcy Lafferty Shatner]], former wife of William Shatner, played the role of Chief DiFalco in [[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]]. *Donna Moore, trainer of American Saddlebred Horses *Melissa Moore, exhibitor of American Saddlebred Horses *Lynn Weatherman, editor, ''The American Saddlebred'' *Horses: Imperator, Sky Watch, Sultan's Great Day, and Miss O'Hare
==Background/production== [[Post-production]] and distribution of the episode was handled by PBS affiliate [[WKNO (TV)]] in Memphis, TN. WKNO was a member entry station for [[American Program Service]] (APS){{efn|In 1999, American Program Service changed their name to [[American Public Television]]}} which handled broadcast distribution to the public television network comprising PBS member stations. Joe Dixon, an editor with WKNO at the time,<ref name=KNO>{{cite web|url=http://www.knoproductions.com/Images/Mobile92704.pdf|title=KNO Productions|date=January 1, 2014|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> did the post production editing and [[sound mix]] for the program.
==Crew==
*Executive producer, Betty Wills *Narrator, David Henry *Camera, Scott Jewett *Online editing, Joe Dixon *Post production assistants, Mark Majillon and Cynthia Pardy *Production assistant, Christine Chartier *Technical advisors, Patricia Nichols and Lynn Weatherman
==Theme== The episode features the history of the [[American Saddlebred Horse]] as a breed, and [[segue]]s into guest host William Shatner speaking candidly about the preparation and training for horse show competition, breeding, raising and selling horses while guiding viewers on a tour of his Belle Reve Farm near Lexington, KY. Shatner also appears competing at the Lexington Junior League Horse Show and in an interview after his performance. The episode ended with the intense head-to-head competition between two of the all-time greatest [[five-gaited]] Champions of their time, the [[stallion]] [[Sky Watch (horse)|Sky Watch]] and the [[gelding]] [[Imperator (horse)|Imperator]], in the stake competition at the Freedom Hall Civic Center in [[Johnson City, Tennessee]]; referred to by some as "the biggest stage in the show horse industry."<ref name="KHP">{{cite web|title=CH Sky Watch|url=http://www.kyhorsepark.com/equine-theme-park/park-memorials-statues/memorial-walk-champions/ch-sky-watch-bio|website=Kentucky Horse Park|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=Funkhouser>{{cite web|url=http://www.saddlehorsereport.com/news.aspx?cid=1386#.VvQNpcccP6Q|title=A Celebration Of History, A Celebration Of Challenges, A Celebration Of Tomorrow|author=Bob Funkhouser|date=September 15, 2003}}</ref>
==Release== As a pilot episode, A Celebration of Horses: The American Saddlebred was scheduled for four releases nationally on 56 PBS affiliates from November 1993 through October 1995. <ref name=TASB/>{{rp|87}}
==AHSA Award== The program won the 1993 AHSA Award for Broadcast Media Excellence.<ref name=TASB/>{{rp|86}} AHSA Award originated in 1993 as part of the ''Making Strides for Equestrian Sport'' initiative<ref name=HSM>{{cite journal | title=Horse Show Magazine | publisher = American Horse Shows Association | date = March 1994 | volume=59 | issue=3}}</ref> sponsored by the American Horse Shows Association.{{efn|The American Horse Shows Association is now the [[United States Equestrian Federation]]}} The American Saddlebred Horse Association nominated the program's executive director and subsequent winner of the broadcast division.<ref name=TASB/> Wills was one of five recipients to receive the award which was presented to former ASHA president Judy Werner on behalf of Wills at the 1994 American Horse Shows Association convention in Denver, Colorado.<ref name=TASB/>{{rp|86}}
==Notes== {{Notes}}
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Horses in film and television]] [[Category:Documentaries about sports]] [[Category:Documentaries about animals]]

The first [[Athlete of the Year]] award in the [[United States]] was initiated by the [[Associated Press]] (AP) in 1931. At a time when [[women's sports|women in sports]] were not given the same recognition as men, the AP offered a male and a female athlete of the year award to either a professional or amateur [[Sportsperson|athlete]]. The awards are voted on annually by a panel of AP sports editors from across the United States. A large majority of the winners have been Americans. However, non-Americans are also eligible for the honor, and have won on a few occasions.
