{{for|the anime and manga series with a similar name|Eyeshield 21}}
{{Refimprove|date=July 2008}}
[[Image:TTU Helmet Visor.png|thumb|150px|right|Rendering of a [[college football]] helmet with an eyeshield. The [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] banned the use of tinted and reflective visors in 2006.<ref>[http://www.dnronline.com/search_details.php?AID=6002&CHID=3&author=&channelid=3&key=&title= Keep On Tickin’ Posted 2006-08-25: The NCAA hopes its new rules shorten games this season.]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>]]
An '''eyeshield''' is a piece of [[American football|football]] equipment. It is a visor that attaches to the [[football helmet|helmet]] of a player to protect the eyes. It leaves the mouth exposed and covers the eyes and nose. Only clear eyeshields are allowed in high school football as the eyes are needed to be seen while checking for concussions. On the [[college football|college level]], a tinted eyeshield may be used if the player has eye problems. The [[National Football League|NFL]] allows dark visors (smoke or black) and reflective mirror visors, but does not allow colored or iridium visors. 

The first football visors were made by [[Oakley, Inc.|Oakley]] and are currently being made by name brands such as [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] and [[Under Armour, Inc.|Under Armour]] as well as many other sports and eyewear companies.

